\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Help}}\)

Use a ? to pull up information on a package and its arguments

?round

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Data Types}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Checking}}\)

Integer = number with no decimal (set using an L)

typeof(100L)
[1] "integer"

Double = number with decimals

typeof(100.0)
[1] "double"

Character = value-less characters

typeof('100')
[1] "character"

Logical = binary value of True/False or 1/0

typeof(100==100)
[1] "logical"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Use}}\)

Using a double in an operation will return a double

typeof(1.0 + 1L)
[1] "double"

Using just integers will result in integers unless it is division

typeof(1L + 1L)
[1] "integer"
typeof(1L / 1L)
[1] "double"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Conversion}}\)

as.integer()
as.double()
as.character()

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Variables}}\)

variable <- "whatever you want"

Setting a variable to a variable copies the value; it is NOT a link

a <- 1
b <- a

a <- 'see!'
a
[1] "see!"
b
[1] 1

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Factors}}\)

(Making strings into categorical variables)

example_strings <- c("medium", "slow", "slow", "medium", "fast")
class(example_strings)
[1] "character"
[1] "medium" "slow"   "slow"   "medium" "fast"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Categorical Factor}}\)

example_factor <- factor(example_strings)
class(example_factor)
[1] "factor"
[1] medium slow   slow   medium fast  
Levels: fast medium slow


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Ordinal Factor}}\)

example_ordered_factor <- factor(example_strings, 
                                 ordered = TRUE, 
                                 levels = c("slow","medium","fast")
                                 )
class(example_ordered_factor)
[1] "ordered" "factor" 
[1] medium slow   slow   medium fast  
Levels: slow < medium < fast

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Vectors}}\)

(One dimensional array; all the same data type)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Creating}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Basic Vector}}\)

eg_vector <- c(1, 2, 3)
eg_vector
[1] 1 2 3


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Named Vector}}\)

names(eg_vector) <- c("item1", "item2", "item3")
eg_vector
item1 item2 item3 
    1     2     3

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Operations}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Adding Vectors}}\)

Within

sum(eg_vector)
[1] 6

Between

c(1, 2, 3) + c(4, 5, 6) =

c((1 + 4), (2 + 5), (3 + 6)) =

c(5, 7, 9)

A_vector <- c(1, 2, 3)
B_vector <- c(4, 5, 6)
A_vector + B_vector
[1] 5 7 9


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Evaluating}}\)

Testing

A_vector > 2
[1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE

Extracting

A_vector[A_vector > 2]
[1] 3

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Indexing}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a specific item}}\)

eg_vector[1]
item1 
    1


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a set of specific items}}\)

eg_vector[c(1,3)]
item1 item3 
    1     3


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a range of items}}\)

eg_vector[1:3]
item1 item2 item3 
    1     2     3


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a specific named item}}\)

eg_vector["item1"]
item1 
    1

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Editing}}\)

eg_vector["item1"] <- 100

eg_vector
item1 item2 item3 
  100     2     3

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Lists}}\)

(One dimensional array; elements do not have to be related in any way)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Creating}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Basic List}}\)

list(A_vector, B_vector)
[[1]]
[1] 1 2 3

[[2]]
[1] 4 5 6


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Named List}}\)

list("A" = A_vector,
     "B" = B_vector)
$A
[1] 1 2 3

$B
[1] 4 5 6
eg_list <- list(A_vector, B_vector)
names(eg_list) <- c("A", "B")

eg_list
$A
[1] 1 2 3

$B
[1] 4 5 6

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Indexing}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract specific item}}\)

eg_list[[1]]
[1] 1 2 3


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract specific item by name}}\)

eg_list[["A"]]
[1] 1 2 3
eg_list$A
[1] 1 2 3


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract specific item within a specific item}}\)

eg_list[[1]][1]
[1] 1

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Editing}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Combining Lists}}\)

c(eg_list, eg_list)

$B

[[2]]$A

[[2]]$B

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Matrices}}\)

(Two dimensional array; all the same data type)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Creating}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Filling by Row}}\)

matrix(1:9,byrow=TRUE,nrow=3)
     [,1] [,2] [,3]
[1,]    1    2    3
[2,]    4    5    6
[3,]    7    8    9


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Filling by Column}}\)

matrix(1:9,byrow=FALSE,nrow=3)
     [,1] [,2] [,3]
[1,]    1    4    7
[2,]    2    5    8
[3,]    3    6    9


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Naming}}\)

eg_matrix <- matrix(1:9,byrow=TRUE,nrow=3)

rownames(eg_matrix) <- c("MA", "NY", "CO")
colnames(eg_matrix) <- c("2010", "2011", "2013")

eg_matrix
   2010 2011 2013
MA    1    2    3
NY    4    5    6
CO    7    8    9

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Operations}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Row Sums}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Column Sums}}\)

2010 2011 2013 
  12   15   18


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Adding Matrices}}\)

matrix_a <- matrix(1:9,byrow=TRUE,nrow=3)

matrix_b <- matrix(1:9,byrow=FALSE,nrow=3)

matrix_a + matrix_b
     [,1] [,2] [,3]
[1,]    2    6   10
[2,]    6   10   14
[3,]   10   14   18

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Dataframes}}\)

(Two dimensional array; all the same data type within a column, but different columns can have different data types)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Creating}}\)

name <- c("Mercury", "Venus", "Earth", "Mars")
type <- c("Terrestrial", "Terrestrial", "Terrestrial", "Terrestrial")
diameter <- c(0.382, 0.949, 1, 0.532)
rotation <- c(58.64, -243.02, 1, 1.03)
rings <- c(FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE)

planets_df <- data.frame(name, type, diameter, rotation, rings)

planets_df
name type diameter rotation rings
Mercury Terrestrial 0.382 58.64 FALSE
Venus Terrestrial 0.949 -243.02 FALSE
Earth Terrestrial 1.000 1.00 FALSE
Mars Terrestrial 0.532 1.03 FALSE

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Operations}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Order Ascending}}\)

planets_df[order(planets_df$diameter),"name"]
[1] "Mercury" "Mars"    "Venus"   "Earth"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Order Descending}}\)

planets_df[order(planets_df$diameter,decreasing=TRUE),"name"]
[1] "Earth"   "Venus"   "Mars"    "Mercury"

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Indexing}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a specific item}}\)

planets_df[2,1]
[1] "Venus"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a subset}}\)

planets_df[2:3,1:2]
name type
2 Venus Terrestrial
3 Earth Terrestrial


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract a specific subset}}\)

planets_df[c(1,3),1:2]
name type
1 Mercury Terrestrial
3 Earth Terrestrial


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract all rows of a column}}\)

planets_df[,1]
[1] "Mercury" "Venus"   "Earth"   "Mars"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract all columns of a row}}\)

planets_df[1,]
name type diameter rotation rings
Mercury Terrestrial 0.382 58.64 FALSE


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract column by name}}\)

planets_df[,"diameter"]
[1] 0.382 0.949 1.000 0.532
planets_df$rings
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Extract based on values}}\)

planets_df[planets_df$rotation<0,]
name type diameter rotation rings
2 Venus Terrestrial 0.949 -243.02 FALSE

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{If Statements}}\)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Single If}}\)

if (condition) {
  expression
}

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{If/Else}}\)

if (condition) {
  expression_1
} else {
  expression_2
}

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{If and Multiple Elses}}\)

if (condition_1) {
  expression_1
} else if (condition_2) {
  expression_2
} else {
  expression_3
}

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Loops}}\)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{While}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- External Condition}}\)

while (condition) {
  expression
}


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Indexed}}\)

i <- 1

while (i <= 3) {
  print(i)
  
  i <- i + 1
}
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{For}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Iterate over a list}}\)

fruit_list <- c("Apples", "Strawberries", "Bananas")

for (item in fruit_list) {
  print(str_c("I love ",item))
}
[1] "I love Apples"
[1] "I love Strawberries"
[1] "I love Bananas"


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Iterate over a sequence}}\)

for (i in seq_along(1:3)) {
  print(i + 1)
}
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Fill in a new list}}\)

dummy_list <- list()

for (i in seq_along(1:3)) {
  dummy_list[[i]] <- i + 1
}

dummy_list
[[1]]
[1] 2

[[2]]
[1] 3

[[3]]
[1] 4

\(\color{darkblue}{\textbf{Functions}}\)

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Existing}}\)

install.packages("package")
library(package)
update.packages()

  • abs(): Calculate the absolute value.

  • sum(): Calculate the sum of all the values in a data structure.

  • mean(): Calculate the arithmetic mean.

  • round(): Round the values to 0 decimal places by default.

  • seq(): Generate sequences, by specifying the from, to, and by arguments.

  • rep(): Replicate elements of vectors and lists.

  • sort(): Sort a vector in ascending order. Works on numerics, but also on character strings and logicals.

  • rev(): Reverse the elements in a data structures for which reversal is defined.

  • str(): Display the structure of any R object.

  • append(): Merge vectors or lists.

  • is.*(): Check for the class of an R object.

  • as.*(): Convert an R object from one class to another.

  • unlist(): Flatten (possibly embedded) lists to produce a vector.

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Creating}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Basic}}\)

function_name <- function (argument_1, argument_2) {
  expression
}


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Default value for variable}}\)

function_name <- function (argument_1, argument_2 = default_value) {
  expression
}


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Infinite variables}}\)

function_name <- function(...) {
  expression using ...
}


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Adding an error message}}\)

function_name <- function(argument) {
  if (condition) {
    stop("Error message", call. = FALSE)
  }
  expression 
}

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Applying}}\)

  • lapply returns a list
  • sapply tries to return a simplified list as a vector or matrix
  • vapply is like sapply but with the result type specified data type(length)
lapply(vector, existing_function)
sapply(vector, existing_function)
vapply(vector, existing_function, numeric(4))
lapply(c(1, 2, 3), function(x){x + 1})
[[1]]
[1] 2

[[2]]
[1] 3

[[3]]
[1] 4


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Additional arguments}}\)

lapply(vector, existing_function, other_arguments)
lapply(c(1, 2, 3), function(x, y){x^y}, 2)
[[1]]
[1] 1

[[2]]
[1] 4

[[3]]
[1] 9


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- New function}}\)

lapply(vector, function(argument){new_function expression})

Test

\(\color{dodgerblue}{\textbf{Apply}}\)

\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Search}}\)

  • grepl() returns TRUE when a pattern is found in the corresponding character string.
  • grep() returns a vector of indices of the character strings that contains the pattern.
grep(regular_expression, search_location)


\(\color{skyblue}{\textrm{- Replace}}\)

  • sub() replaces the first match
  • gsub() replaces all matches
gep(regular_expression, replace_value, search_location)
